["Sure! Here is a sample software development manager resume for a person named Juan Perez from Buenos Aires who is primarily a Java developer with some Python experience:\n\nJuan Perez\nSoftware Development Manager\nBuenos Aires, Argentina\n\nSummary:\n\nHighly motivated and experienced Software Development Manager with a strong background in Java development and experience with Python. Proven track record of leading successful software development projects and teams, driving innovation and continuous improvement, and delivering high-quality solutions on time and within budget. Skilled in project management, agile methodologies, and software design and architecture.\n\nSkills:\n\n* Java development\n* Python\n* Project management\n* Agile methodologies\n* Software design and architecture\n* Team leadership\n* Communication and collaboration\n* Problem-solving and critical thinking\n\nExperience:\n\nSoftware Development Manager\nABC Company, Buenos Aires, Argentina (20XX-present)\n\n* Led a team of 15 software developers in the design, development, and delivery of several successful software projects using Java and Python.\n* Implemented agile methodologies, including Scrum and Kanban, to improve team productivity and deliver high-quality solutions on time.\n* Developed and maintained software design and architecture documentation to ensure that projects were scalable, maintainable, and aligned with business goals.\n* Collaborated with cross-functional teams, including product management, QA, and operations, to define and prioritize project requirements and deliverables.\n* Mentored and coached team members to help them grow their technical and professional skills.\n\nSenior Software Developer\nXYZ Company, Buenos Aires, Argentina (20XX-20XX)\n\n* Contributed to the development of several software projects using Java and Python.\n* Worked closely with the development team to design and implement software solutions that met business needs and requirements.\n* Participated in code reviews, pair programming, and other software development best practices to ensure high-quality code.\n\nEducation:\n\n* Bachelor's Degree in Computer Science, University of Buenos Aires (20XX-20XX)\n\nCertifications:\n\n* Certified Scrum Master (CSM)\n* Certified Java Developer (CJD)\n\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance.", 'Sure, instead of a hierarchy, we can represent the different grammatical units as layers in a "layer cake" model, where each layer is made up of the layers below it.\n\nAt the top level, we have Sentences, which are made up of Clauses (Independent and Dependent) and Phrases.\n\nThe next level down is made up of Phrases, which can be found in both clauses and independently in a sentence.\n\nThe next level down is made up of Words, which can be found in phrases, clauses and sentences.\n\nThe bottom level is made up of Letters, which make up words.\n\nAs for the separate layer cake for subject, predicate, object and complement, they can be considered as separate layers that can be added to the main layer cake. They are grammatical roles that can be assigned to different parts of the sentence, for example, subject can be a noun phrase, predicate can be a verb phrase, object can be a noun phrase and complement can be an adjective phrase.\n\nSo the main layer cake of Sentences, Clauses, Phrases, Words and letters can be modified by adding the layers of subject, predicate, object and complement to the different parts of the sentence, depending on the context and the language structure.\n\nI hope this helps in visualizing how the different grammatical units can be represented as layers in a "layer cake" model and how the different grammatical roles can be added to it.\nPlease let me know if you have any other question.', "To fill a half-full tank in 10 minutes while also draining it at a constant rate, the rate at which water is pumped in must be twice the rate at which it is drained. Since it takes 30 minutes to empty the tank by draining it at a constant rate, the rate at which it is drained is 1/30 of the tank's capacity per minute. Therefore, the rate at which water must be pumped in is 2 \\* (1/30) of the tank's capacity per minute, or 2/30 of the tank's capacity per minute."]

