['"The Seven Husbands of Evelyn Hugo" is a wonderful book! If you loved its blend of contemporary fiction, Hollywood glamour, and emotional depth, here are some fiction novel recommendations that you might enjoy:\n\n1. **The Devil Wears Prada** by Lauren Weisberger: While not exactly similar, this bestselling novel shares some of the same themes of glamour, celebrity, and the highs and lows of the entertainment industry.\n2. **The Address** by Fiona Davis: This novel explores the lives of the residents and staff at the iconic Dakota apartment building in New York City, weaving a tale of love, loss, and secrets, much like Evelyn Hugo\'s story.\n3. **The Royal We** by Heather Cocks and Jessica Morgan: This novel follows an American college student who falls for a British prince, and the drama that ensues. Like Evelyn Hugo, it\'s a juicy, addictive read with a strong female protagonist.\n4. **Daisy Jones and The Six** by Taylor Jenkins Reid (yes, the same author!): While not exactly similar in style, this novel shares some of the same themes of fame, love, and the music industry. It\'s a fantastic read that explores the rise and fall of a fictional rock band in the 1970s.\n5. **The Last Romantics** by Tara Conklin: This novel follows a family\'s secrets and struggles across multiple generations, exploring themes of love, loss, and the power of stories, much like Evelyn Hugo\'s tale.\n6. **The Age of Light** by Whitney Scharer: This novel is based on the life of Lee Miller, a model and photographer who was a muse to Man Ray. It\'s a beautifully written story about art, love, and identity, with a similar atmosphere of glamour and creativity.\n7. **The Dollhouse** by Fiona Davis: Another novel by Davis, this one explores the lives of two women living in the same New York City apartment building, 50 years apart. It\'s a story of love, loss, and secrets, with a similar sense of nostalgia and glamour.\n8. **The Last Equation of Isaac Severy** by Nova Jacobs: This novel follows a young woman who inherits a mysterious equation from her grandfather, a famous mathematician. It\'s a story about family secrets, love, and the power of stories, with a similar sense of intrigue and mystery.\n\nThese novels offer a mix of glamour, drama, and emotional depth that fans of "The Seven Husbands of Evelyn Hugo" are likely to enjoy. Happy reading!', 'The spread of religion in the 6th century had a significant impact on trade and commerce in several ways. \n\nFirstly, religion played a significant role in shaping cultural and societal norms, which in turn affected the ways in which people engaged in trade and commerce. For instance, religious beliefs and practices influenced the types of goods and services that were considered acceptable or taboo, and also impacted the attitudes towards profit and wealth accumulation. \n\nSecondly, the spread of religion often led to the establishment of religious centers and pilgrimage sites that attracted large numbers of people, creating opportunities for trade and commerce. Merchants could supply goods and services to pilgrims and religious leaders, and the increased flow of people through these areas created a demand for food, lodging, souvenirs, and other goods. \n\nThirdly, some religious orders were active in trade and commerce themselves. For example, monasteries often engaged in agriculture, craftsmanship, and trade as a means of sustaining themselves financially. The power and wealth of these religious institutions could in turn impact the broader economy of a region. \n\nOverall, the spread of religion in the 6th century had complex and multifaceted effects on trade and commerce, shaping economic practices and opportunities in a variety of ways.', 'Great to hear that you\'re looking to get back into playing the guitar! Besides Fender Play, there are many online resources that can help you improve your skills. Here are some popular ones:\n\n1. **Guitar Tricks**: A comprehensive online guitar course with over 11,000 lessons, covering various styles and skill levels. They offer a 14-day free trial, and then it\'s $19.95/month.\n2. **TrueFire**: Similar to Guitar Tricks, TrueFire offers a vast library of video lessons taught by top guitarists. They have a free trial, and then it\'s $29.95/month or $299.95/year.\n3. **Justin Guitar**: A free online guitar course with a comprehensive beginner\'s course, as well as lessons on specific styles like blues, rock, and jazz. Justin\'s teaching style is friendly and approachable.\n4. **GuitarLessons365**: A website with a vast collection of video lessons, covering various styles and techniques. They offer a free trial, and then it\'s $29.95/month or $299.95/year.\n5. **Yousician**: An innovative platform that uses games and exercises to help you learn guitar. It\'s available as a mobile app (iOS and Android) or on the web. They offer a free trial, and then it\'s $19.95/month or $119.88/year.\n6. **ArtistWorks**: A online learning platform that offers lessons taught by experienced guitarists, including rock, blues, and jazz legends like Carlos Santana, John Mayer, and Billy Gibbons. They offer a free trial, and then it\'s $29.95/month or $299.95/year.\n7. **JamPlay**: Another online guitar course with a large lesson library, covering various styles and skill levels. They offer a free trial, and then it\'s $29.95/month or $299.95/year.\n8. **Ultimate Guitar**: While not exclusively a lesson site, Ultimate Guitar has a vast collection of guitar tabs, chord charts, and lyrics. They also offer a "Lessons" section with video tutorials and articles.\n9. **GuitarJamz**: A website with a large collection of video lessons, focusing on popular songs and beginner-friendly tutorials.\n10. **YouTube**: Don\'t forget about YouTube! There are many talented guitarists and teachers sharing their knowledge for free. You can search for specific lessons, techniques, or songs to learn.\n\nRemember, the key to improving your guitar skills is consistent practice. Supplement these online resources with regular playing, and you\'ll see progress in no time!']

