['Acknowledged.', "Congratulations on getting back into guitar playing!\n\nIt's great that you have a patient instructor like Alex to guide you. Given your background and recent restart, I'd recommend a hybrid approach:\n\n**Build up your calluses, but don't wait too long to try ukulele**\n\nHere's why:\n\n1. **Re-building calluses takes time**: It's essential to rebuild your calluses to avoid discomfort and pain while playing. However, if you focus solely on building calluses, you might delay starting ukulele for too long.\n2. **Ukulele can help with callus building**: The ukulele's softer strings and shorter scale length can actually help you build up your calluses more gently than a guitar. This can be a good opportunity to work on your calluses while exploring a new instrument.\n3. **Ukulele can be a great supplement**: Learning ukulele can help you develop finger independence, dexterity, and strength, which will also benefit your guitar playing. You can alternate between guitar and ukulele practice to keep your fingers engaged and active.\n\nHere's a suggested approach:\n\n1. **Continue guitar lessons with Alex**: Focus on rebuilding your calluses and improving your guitar skills. Aim to practice guitar for 20-30 minutes, 3-4 times a week.\n2. **Introduce ukulele practice**: Start with short ukulele practice sessions (10-15 minutes, 1-2 times a week) to get comfortable with the instrument and build up your calluses. You can begin with simple chords, fingerpicking patterns, or even just getting familiar with the ukulele's feel and tuning.\n3. **Alternate between guitar and ukulele**: As you become more comfortable with the ukulele, you can alternate between guitar and ukulele practice sessions. This will help you maintain progress on both instruments and keep your fingers active.\n\nRemember to:\n\n* Start with shorter practice sessions and gradually increase the duration as your calluses build up.\n* Be gentle with your fingers and take regular breaks to avoid fatigue and discomfort.\n* Communicate with Alex about your ukulele practice and ask for guidance on how to balance your practice sessions.\n\nBy following this approach, you'll be able to rebuild your calluses, improve your guitar skills, and explore the ukulele without feeling overwhelmed. Good luck, and have fun!", "The Italian-Style Salad will pair beautifully with your spaghetti dinner.\n\nNow, about those garlic knots... Making them from scratch can be a bit tricky, but with some tips and tricks, you'll be a pro in no time! Here's a simple recipe to get you started:\n\n**Homemade Garlic Knots Recipe:**\n\nIngredients:\n\n* 1 1/2 cups warm water\n* 2 teaspoons active dry yeast\n* 3 tablespoons olive oil\n* 1 teaspoon salt\n* 3 cloves garlic, minced\n* 3 cups all-purpose flour\n* 1 egg, beaten (for egg wash)\n* Parmesan cheese, grated (optional)\n\nTips and Tricks:\n\n1. **Use a high-quality yeast**: Make sure your yeast is fresh and active to ensure the dough rises properly.\n2. **Don't overmix the dough**: Mix the ingredients just until they come together in a shaggy ball. Overmixing can lead to tough garlic knots.\n3. **Let the dough rise**: Allow the dough to rise for at least 1 hour, or until it's doubled in size. This will give the garlic knots a light and airy texture.\n4. **Use a gentle touch**: When shaping the dough into knots, be gentle to avoid developing the gluten in the flour. This will help the garlic knots stay soft and tender.\n5. **Don't overbake**: Garlic knots are best when they're lightly golden brown. Overbaking can make them dry and crispy.\n\nHere's a simple recipe to follow:\n\n1. In a large bowl, combine warm water, yeast, and a pinch of sugar. Let it sit for 5-10 minutes, or until the yeast is activated.\n2. Add olive oil, salt, garlic, and 2 cups of flour to the bowl. Mix until a shaggy ball forms.\n3. Gradually add the remaining cup of flour, one tablespoon at a time, until the dough comes together in a sticky ball.\n4. Knead the dough for 5-7 minutes, until it becomes smooth and elastic.\n5. Place the dough in a greased bowl, cover it with plastic wrap, and let it rise in a warm place for 1 hour, or until doubled in size.\n6. Preheat your oven to 375°F (190°C). Line a baking sheet with parchment paper.\n7. Punch down the dough and divide it into 8-10 equal pieces. Roll each piece into a long rope and tie a knot in the center.\n8. Place the garlic knots on the prepared baking sheet, leaving about 1 inch of space between each knot.\n9. Brush the tops with beaten egg and sprinkle with Parmesan cheese (if using).\n10. Bake for 12-15 minutes, or until lightly golden brown.\n\nThat's it! Your homemade garlic knots are ready to be devoured. Serve them warm as an appetizer, and enjoy with your spaghetti dinner and Italian-Style Salad. Buon appetito!"]

