['| Name | Affiliation | Major Works | Field of Specialty | Significant Idea or Theory | Similar Theorists | How Similar? | Contrarian Theorists | How Contrary? |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| Fei Xiaotong (费孝通) | Peking University (北京大学, 北京大學), London School of Economics | From the Soil, Peasant Life in China | Sociology, Anthropology | "Rural-Urban Continuum" - viewing rural and urban areas as a continuous spectrum | Ray Huang | Ray Huang also examines the rural-urban relationship, emphasizing how rural and urban economies are interconnected; Quote: "the rural-urban divide has long been blurred in China" | Saskia Sassen | Saskia Sassen emphasizes the global city concept, which may overlook the rural-urban continuum; Quote: "Global cities are strategic places where global processes are most deeply embedded" |\n| Wang Hui (汪晖) | Tsinghua University (清华大学, 清華大學) | The End of the Revolution, China\'s Twentieth Century | Intellectual History, Political Science | "New Left" - critiquing neoliberalism and advocating for social justice in China | Cui Zhiyuan | Cui Zhiyuan shares similar concerns about neoliberalism and its impact on Chinese society; Quote: "The neoliberal model is not suitable for China\'s development" | Zhang Weiying | Zhang Weiying argues for the benefits of market-oriented reforms; Quote: "Market-oriented reforms have significantly improved people\'s lives and economic efficiency in China" |\n| Pun Ngai (潘毅) | Hong Kong Polytechnic University (香港理工大学, 香港理工大學) | Made in China, Migrant Labor in China | Sociology, Labor Studies | "Dormitory Labor Regime" - the relationship between living conditions and labor | Ching Kwan Lee | Ching Kwan Lee similarly investigates the labor conditions and labor rights of migrant workers; Quote: "The export-oriented manufacturing sector is built on the exploitation of migrant labor" | Elizabeth J. Perry | Elizabeth J. Perry focuses on the role of grassroots organizations in labor rights, which might overshadow the dormitory labor regime; Quote: "Grassroots organizations have been crucial in labor rights" |\n| Yan Yunxiang (晏雲翔) | University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) | The Individualization of Chinese Society | Anthropology, Sociology | "Individualization" - exploring the growing importance of individual identity | Zhang Li (characters unknown) | Zhang Li examines how individual identity and autonomy are becoming more important in modern China; Quote: "Individuals increasingly seek self-expression and personal fulfillment in a rapidly changing society" | Robert J. Barnett (characters unknown) | Robert J. Barnett emphasizes the role of collective identity in shaping Chinese society; Quote: "Collective identity remains an important aspect of Chinese culture and social organization" |\n| Vanessa Fong | Amherst College | Only Hope, Paradise Redefined | Anthropology, Education | "One-Child Generation" - the social and psychological impact of China\'s one-child policy | Susan Greenhalgh (characters unknown) | Susan Greenhalgh also explores the consequences of the one-child policy on Chinese society; Quote: "The one |  |  |', "Let's calculate the temperature rise (ΔT) using the provided values:\n\nQ = 2.53 J (heat generated, as calculated earlier)\nm = 24000 kg (mass of the affected concrete)\nc = 880 J/kg°C (specific heat capacity of the concrete)\nT\\_initial = 30°C (initial temperature of the concrete, assuming summer temperature)\n\nUsing the formula ΔT = Q / (m \\* c), we can calculate the temperature rise:\n\nΔT = Q / (m \\* c)\nΔT = 2.53 J / (24000 kg \\* 880 J/kg°C)\nΔT ≈ 1.19 × 10^-7 °C\n\nThe temperature rise is approximately 1.19 × 10^-7 °C. Now, let's add this temperature rise to the initial temperature to get the final temperature:\n\nT\\_final = T\\_initial + ΔT\nT\\_final = 30°C + 1.19 × 10^-7 °C\nT\\_final ≈ 30°C\n\nThe final temperature is approximately 30°C, which is well within the allowable temperature range of 65-93°C for concrete. The temperature rise is extremely small in this case, and the final temperature remains essentially unchanged.", 'Here are three more delicious meal ideas that incorporate many of the foods from the list above to support cognitive health:\n\n1. Spinach and Feta Stuffed Chicken Breast with Roasted Vegetables and Quinoa\n\nIngredients:\n\n* Chicken breast (poultry)\n* Fresh spinach (leafy green vegetable)\n* Feta cheese (dairy product)\n* Olive oil\n* Salt and pepper\n* Garlic powder\n* Quinoa (whole grain)\n* Assorted vegetables (such as zucchini, bell peppers, and cherry tomatoes)\n* Fresh parsley\n\nInstructions:\n\n* Preheat the oven to 375°F (190°C).\n* Make a horizontal cut in each chicken breast to create a pocket for the stuffing.\n* In a bowl, mix together chopped fresh spinach and crumbled feta cheese.\n* Stuff each chicken breast with the spinach and feta mixture, then season the outside with salt, pepper, and garlic powder.\n* Heat olive oil in an oven-safe skillet over medium heat. Sear the stuffed chicken breasts for 2-3 minutes on each side, then transfer the skillet to the oven and bake for 20-25 minutes or until cooked through.\n* Cook quinoa according to package instructions.\n* Toss the assorted vegetables in olive oil, salt, and pepper, and spread them out on a lined baking sheet. Roast in the oven for 20-25 minutes or until tender.\n* Serve the spinach and feta stuffed chicken breasts with roasted vegetables and quinoa, garnished with fresh parsley.\n1. Seared Tuna with Sesame Broccoli and Brown Rice\n\nIngredients:\n\n* Tuna steak (fatty fish)\n* Olive oil\n* Salt and pepper\n* Brown rice (whole grain)\n* Broccoli (vegetable)\n* Soy sauce\n* Sesame oil\n* Honey\n* Garlic\n* Ginger\n* Sesame seeds\n* Green onions\n\nInstructions:\n\n* Cook brown rice according to package instructions.\n* Season the tuna steak with salt and pepper. Heat olive oil in a skillet over medium-high heat, and sear the tuna for 2-3 minutes on each side (or until cooked to desired doneness). Set aside.\n* In a separate skillet or wok, heat sesame oil over medium heat. Add minced garlic and ginger, and cook until fragrant.\n* Add broccoli florets to the skillet, and cook until tender but still crisp. In a small bowl, whisk together soy sauce, honey, and a splash of sesame oil, then pour the sauce over the broccoli.\n* Sprinkle sesame seeds over the broccoli and toss to combine.\n* Serve the seared tuna with sesame broccoli and brown rice, garnished with green onions.\n1. Lentil and Vegetable Curry with Whole Grain Naan\n\nIngredients:\n\n* Red or green lentils (legumes)\n* Olive oil\n* Onion\n* Garlic\n* Ginger\n* Curry powder\n* Turmeric\n* Cumin\n* Red pepper flakes\n* Canned diced tomatoes\n* Coconut milk\n* Carrots (vegetable)\n* Green beans (vegetable)\n* Red bell pepper (vegetable)\n* Spinach (leafy green vegetable)\n* Salt and pepper\n* Fresh cilantro\n* Whole grain naan (whole grain)\n\nInstructions:\n\n* Cook lentils according to package instructions.\n* In a large pot, heat olive oil over medium heat. Add chopped onion, minced garlic, and grated ginger, and cook until softened.\n* Add curry powder, turmeric, cumin, and red pepper flakes, and cook for 1-2 minutes until fragrant.\n* Stir in canned diced tomatoes and coconut milk, and bring the mixture to a simmer.\n* Add chopped carrots, green beans, and red bell pepper, and cook until the vegetables are tender.\n*']

